1
00:00:03,963 --> 00:00:22,797
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambodassam Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambodassam

2
00:00:23,285 --> 00:00:40,350
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Samma Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:40,371 --> 00:00:51,046
I like to start with that little chant just to remind myself what I'm supposed to be doing, which is to express the Buddha's teaching and not my own peculiar understandings.

4
00:00:53,119 --> 00:01:05,408
So this morning really it's just a little revision for most of you about the principles of meditation and maybe for some of you just an introduction.

5
00:01:12,930 --> 00:01:38,635
the Buddha is very sort of clear about his teachings even though we have masses of scriptures stories and teachings that come from his time they're all you know really pointing to this this one and same thing that he reduced his whole teaching to he was only concerned with dukkha and the end of dukkha this word is

6
00:01:38,715 --> 00:01:40,998
really kernel to his teachings.

7
00:01:41,019 --> 00:01:44,602
There's no single English word that grasps its meaning.

8
00:01:45,322 --> 00:01:50,688
It's basically anything that you would consider to be unsatisfactory, suffering.

9
00:01:52,331 --> 00:02:03,403
So it traverses the whole gamut of human misery from the slightest discomfort to the deepest despair, panic, all that sort of stuff.

10
00:02:03,424 --> 00:02:04,605
But it also

11
00:02:04,584 --> 00:02:11,933
is around something that we mentioned this morning, around indulgence and our relationship to the pleasures and joys of life.

12
00:02:14,257 --> 00:02:22,366
And so he says that the whole of his teaching is around that and the end of that, and the end of that suffering.

13
00:02:23,008 --> 00:02:29,496
And the core problem lies in identity.

14
00:02:30,842 --> 00:02:37,750
Once we've grasped that, then we can really begin to undermine a lot of our suffering.

15
00:02:37,770 --> 00:02:39,170
Identity is when you say, I am.

16
00:02:39,191 --> 00:02:40,793
I am.

17
00:02:41,514 --> 00:02:44,417
So, I am unhappy.

18
00:02:44,836 --> 00:02:45,858
Well, how can you get out of that?

19
00:02:47,860 --> 00:02:51,544
If you say, I am depressed, what way is there out of that?

20
00:02:51,883 --> 00:02:52,824
That's what you are.

21
00:02:53,705 --> 00:02:54,187
You see what I mean?

22
00:02:54,227 --> 00:02:55,888
You've blocked yourself in.

23
00:02:55,907 --> 00:02:59,431
You've built this wall around this depression called me.

24
00:03:00,694 --> 00:03:01,855
I am hungry.

25
00:03:02,276 --> 00:03:02,757
What can you do?

26
00:03:03,758 --> 00:03:06,080
You've got to eat.

27
00:03:06,480 --> 00:03:08,002
There's no way out of I am.

28
00:03:08,042 --> 00:03:16,510
And so the core of the teaching lies around this problem of identity and its secondary problem of possession.

29
00:03:18,752 --> 00:03:27,241
So once you say I am a human being, big problems arise.

30
00:03:28,741 --> 00:03:32,691
Of course, I'm not suggesting that, conventionally speaking, we're not human beings.

31
00:03:32,711 --> 00:03:36,300
I mean, we are different from other beings.

32
00:03:36,319 --> 00:03:45,282
But something goes awry when we make that very deep connection with this form of life.

33
00:03:45,969 --> 00:03:50,435
That connection is about being happy.

34
00:03:50,895 --> 00:03:55,762
I mean, if you were to ask anybody in the world, you know, what do they want to be, they'd be happy.

35
00:03:55,782 --> 00:04:01,889
See, I mean, they might have all sorts of definitions as to what happiness means, but they all want to be happy.

36
00:04:03,471 --> 00:04:07,776
And therefore, we seek happiness in the world.

37
00:04:08,887 --> 00:04:21,916
So that's where things go wrong, because nothing in this world can really fulfill the deep desire to be in a continuous state of happiness, because nothing lasts.

38
00:04:21,937 --> 00:04:23,841
It's a big problem for us.

39
00:04:24,057 --> 00:04:29,867
So as soon as I have something which makes me happy, I form a relationship to it.

40
00:04:30,208 --> 00:04:32,892
I say, well, this is me or this is mine.

41
00:04:34,134 --> 00:04:47,077
So if I'm feeling good, you know, I've just been successful at something or I've just met a good friend and all that sort of stuff, I say I'm happy, see?

42
00:04:48,374 --> 00:04:57,747
And once I found a situation, once I found an environment, a circumstance which makes me happy, then of course there's an actual tendency to just want to continue it.

43
00:04:58,369 --> 00:05:00,831
It's like, the party was great, let's have another one.

44
00:05:01,432 --> 00:05:03,896
It's just the next one's never quite up to it, is it?

45
00:05:05,019 --> 00:05:16,896
So this grasping, that's what we mean by this grasping, this attachment, is whenever something happens to us which we associate with happiness,

46
00:05:17,331 --> 00:05:43,896
then of course we want to hold it want to maintain it and if possible to make it grow and if it's something that we have then of course we want to make sure that we protect it if you have a car you know have a mobile then there's a sort of relationship with this object which you don't have with other people's cars and other people's mobiles it's like it's mine

47
00:05:45,057 --> 00:05:47,379
Do you know what I mean?

48
00:05:47,439 --> 00:05:56,713
And it's not only a psychological dependency now, because you get very upset if somebody steals your mobile, it's a legal fiction, isn't it?

49
00:05:57,053 --> 00:06:07,369
I mean, if somebody steals something of yours, your mobile, I mean, you go around saying, you know, somebody stole my mobile, see?

50
00:06:07,500 --> 00:06:09,023
as though it was still yours.

51
00:06:09,764 --> 00:06:10,605
It's ridiculous, isn't it?

52
00:06:10,646 --> 00:06:13,069
Because it now belongs to the thief.

53
00:06:14,331 --> 00:06:16,634
They're the ones who have the mobile.

54
00:06:17,896 --> 00:06:31,317
So, when we look at our relationship to the things that we experience and the things that we have, and we look at them closely, then we can see it's actually causing some sort of psychological dependency.

55
00:06:32,680 --> 00:06:33,821
It's a form of addiction.

56
00:06:35,223 --> 00:06:35,584
And

57
00:06:36,221 --> 00:06:43,994
Whenever we do that, if things change, then it produces the other side of happiness which is unhappiness.

58
00:06:46,237 --> 00:06:47,839
That's only one side of the equation.

59
00:06:49,442 --> 00:06:51,524
The other side is this business of aversion.

60
00:06:52,185 --> 00:06:58,276
So now we're into really fending off anybody who undermines my happiness.

61
00:06:59,497 --> 00:07:04,524
And that puts me into a state of aversion, of hatred, of wanting to get rid of the person.

62
00:07:05,264 --> 00:07:10,610
my life would be really happy if you would just disappear, if you'd go away, leave me alone.

63
00:07:11,550 --> 00:07:19,699
And then if it's too much, I'm into the obverse of fear, of hatred and aversion, which is fear and anxiety.

64
00:07:20,841 --> 00:07:22,002
These two are very close.

65
00:07:22,081 --> 00:07:35,136
If when they arise in you, you actually experience them as sensation, not as an emotion, a named emotion, you'll find that the sensations around those things are very close.

66
00:07:35,605 --> 00:07:42,725
You'll find, I'm sure, that hatred is very cold like fear and anxiety is very hot like anger.

67
00:07:43,848 --> 00:07:50,509
And at a sensation base, it's often quite difficult to sometimes see a distinction between them.

68
00:07:52,057 --> 00:07:58,225
It's the mind which produces the definition and the consequent action that we take.

69
00:07:59,127 --> 00:08:06,115
So here we have a real duality of behavior in the world where we're constantly in conflict.

70
00:08:06,956 --> 00:08:11,302
Every so often we do reach a sort of stasis, a place that we might call sort of happiness.

71
00:08:11,742 --> 00:08:12,884
It never lasts.

72
00:08:12,903 --> 00:08:19,651
And so we find ourselves constantly holding on to something, making sure it doesn't move, doesn't change, or we want to get rid of something.

73
00:08:20,358 --> 00:08:23,343
So our lives, even at a very simple level, are a conflict.

74
00:08:24,386 --> 00:08:29,095
So you're lying in bed and suddenly you feel uncomfortable, the body feels uncomfortable.

75
00:08:29,355 --> 00:08:29,956
So you've got to move.

76
00:08:30,096 --> 00:08:36,730
If you don't move, you start getting angry with yourself, angry with the bed, it's not quite the right bed, and so on.

77
00:08:36,710 --> 00:08:51,947
It's like when you catch that this deep relationship that we have with this body, this psycho-physical organism, then you see that something's gone wrong at a very deep, profound level.

78
00:08:52,467 --> 00:08:54,551
And that's what we're chasing in our meditation.

79
00:08:54,571 --> 00:09:02,379
We're trying to see the consequences of this and go back on the process to find out where the original mistake is made.

80
00:09:03,676 --> 00:09:07,582
Now that original mistake is what the Buddha calls the delusion.

81
00:09:08,686 --> 00:09:16,000
And it arises out of, really, a very innocent state, which is often translated as ignorance.

82
00:09:17,341 --> 00:09:19,687
But ignorance gives it a sort of pejorative meaning.

83
00:09:19,706 --> 00:09:21,269
It's as though you should have known.

84
00:09:21,309 --> 00:09:23,453
But actually it's a state of not knowing.

85
00:09:24,917 --> 00:09:25,717
So it's a very...

86
00:09:26,895 --> 00:09:43,518
It's a very open state in which simply by not knowing the way things really are, so there's a little pat phrase from the Buddha to see things as they really are, to see and understand things as they really are, we just made a simple mistake, right?

87
00:09:43,918 --> 00:09:45,980
Although it's simple, it's also profound.

88
00:09:46,981 --> 00:09:55,013
And the fact is that the society we're born into supports that mistake, supports it completely, right?

89
00:09:55,297 --> 00:10:12,158
And in these days, of course, with our materialism and our materialistic science and materialistic understandings, that's not all of us, of course, but with that sort of understanding

90
00:10:12,796 --> 00:10:26,991
subsisting a lot of what our society does, then it completely turns us all towards this life, what this life can give us as a source of true happiness.

91
00:10:28,974 --> 00:10:41,688
So all the Buddha's saying is, look, you know, really investigate this stuff, try to find out whether in fact where you're putting your energy, where you're putting your investments, whether in fact you're getting a decent return.

92
00:10:42,715 --> 00:10:52,304
And when you begin to look at it from that point of view in the beginning, then there comes this sort of doubt as to whether in fact, you know, we're sort of chasing the right thing here.

93
00:10:53,870 --> 00:10:54,631
So...

94
00:10:57,565 --> 00:11:04,916
One of the mistakes that we can make is to think that therefore the Buddha is saying that what we have to get rid of is all pleasures and all joys of life.

95
00:11:04,936 --> 00:11:07,399
But that would be one step too far.

96
00:11:08,039 --> 00:11:10,123
He's not negative towards life.

97
00:11:10,163 --> 00:11:13,807
He himself knows when he's having a beautiful meal.

98
00:11:14,288 --> 00:11:19,716
He knows when he's eating, but he also knows that there is no greed involved.

99
00:11:20,477 --> 00:11:27,488
Now that greed is something to do with our relationship to food that we mentioned this morning, seeking happiness in food.

100
00:11:28,177 --> 00:11:38,969
And therefore, one would think, well, if I don't seek happiness in food, therefore the food becomes tasteless, or I lose interest in food, or I don't even want to know about food.

101
00:11:39,549 --> 00:11:42,513
But that would be a step too far, right?

102
00:11:42,533 --> 00:11:46,076
We have to understand that the body is always going to give us pleasure and pain.

103
00:11:46,798 --> 00:11:49,461
So when pleasure arises, it's to be appreciated.

104
00:11:50,201 --> 00:11:55,888
It's to be enjoyed, but somehow not to be seen as a source of happiness.

105
00:11:56,307 --> 00:12:04,360
When the heart responds with joy and you're in a state of peace and calm, that's beautiful, right?

106
00:12:04,380 --> 00:12:06,804
It's to be appreciated, it's to be enjoyed.

107
00:12:07,024 --> 00:12:10,289
But if you think that's real happiness, then there's a problem.

108
00:12:10,309 --> 00:12:16,019
Because if you think that emotions, that the emotional life is happiness,

109
00:12:16,404 --> 00:12:21,461
then you're always going to try and manipulate the whole of life to make yourself feel happy.

110
00:12:22,484 --> 00:12:28,001
And that produces a real sort of conflict within us because life just won't do it.

111
00:12:29,517 --> 00:12:34,644
Even people, you know, people who sometimes delight us are sometimes extraordinarily painful.

112
00:12:35,465 --> 00:12:36,787
And of course, we to them.

113
00:12:39,029 --> 00:12:48,403
And it's just that natural ability to see that the emotional life is not really where true happiness lies.

114
00:12:49,480 --> 00:12:52,222
So now, then we're left with the intellect.

115
00:12:52,263 --> 00:12:54,264
Then we're left with thought and imagination.

116
00:12:55,066 --> 00:12:58,149
And what we realize through our meditation is that it's absolutely rampant.

117
00:12:59,250 --> 00:13:04,534
I mean, most people, I think, before they begin to meditate, think that they are in control of their minds.

118
00:13:05,176 --> 00:13:09,539
They think what they want to think and feel what they want to feel.

119
00:13:10,260 --> 00:13:14,686
Then when they come to meditation, try and sit still, they realize, actually, they're berserk.

120
00:13:14,706 --> 00:13:15,826
They're absolutely nutters.

121
00:13:16,067 --> 00:13:19,149
The mind simply goes absolutely AWOL.

122
00:13:20,006 --> 00:13:36,631
And then you realize that actually, for the most of people's lives, they're acting in a very automatic, automaton way, that decisions are made before they know about them, and then they say that they've actually made this decision.

123
00:13:36,751 --> 00:13:40,918
But it's made at a subconscious level because it's habitual.

124
00:13:40,898 --> 00:13:50,331
And this came up in some tests that some scientists did about this sort of stuff, where they do brain scans and they can tell when somebody's made a decision.

125
00:13:51,253 --> 00:13:56,941
And the decision comes before they actually recognize that they've made a decision.

126
00:13:57,701 --> 00:14:01,187
Now that, in Buddhist understanding, is the mindless life.

127
00:14:01,628 --> 00:14:03,210
That's exactly...

128
00:14:03,190 --> 00:14:27,139
it's exactly how we often behave even you know people who've been in meditation for a long time find themselves behaving in that mindless way because it's habitual right it just it just happens but then there's this little trick that we play on ourselves where we actually think or we somehow experience that as me making that decision

129
00:14:27,996 --> 00:14:39,087
Now, what our meditation is trying to do is to waken us up and to be in that state of alertness so that we actually see this movement in the mind and heart of an intention.

130
00:14:39,609 --> 00:14:43,852
And it's at the point of intention that we can take control.

131
00:14:43,893 --> 00:14:53,903
Because if that intention, we see that intention as being unwholesome, then we have to sort of relax around it, not to be governed by it.

132
00:14:53,883 --> 00:15:04,817
And we find that just by letting that energy, that desire, die away, we're actually undermining that conditioning that we ourselves have put there.

133
00:15:04,836 --> 00:15:11,225
And every time we see something which is wholesome, then you decide to do it, you empower it.

134
00:15:11,605 --> 00:15:18,134
And in that way, the conditioning that we are reinforcing grows for us.

135
00:15:19,903 --> 00:15:25,149
So you might feel, for instance, lethargic during the day for no reason, really.

136
00:15:25,188 --> 00:15:25,889
You've slept well.

137
00:15:25,909 --> 00:15:27,412
There's no reason to feel tired.

138
00:15:27,812 --> 00:15:37,662
But it's more to do with the dullness that we suffer from, the lethargy that we suffer from, which is often, for most people, a big hindrance in the meditation.

139
00:15:37,822 --> 00:15:39,043
As soon as you sit, you fall asleep.

140
00:15:40,846 --> 00:15:43,447
And in daily life, you might find just feeling a bit tired.

141
00:15:43,528 --> 00:15:48,813
So without really thinking, you just lay out on the couch, head for the bed, all that sort of stuff.

142
00:15:50,126 --> 00:15:54,035
And unfortunately, without us knowing it, we're reinforcing that little habit.

143
00:15:54,277 --> 00:16:02,735
It feels nice, it feels good, but it builds up within us this habit of seeking happiness in sleep.

144
00:16:04,066 --> 00:16:05,629
Seeking an escape in sleep.

145
00:16:06,591 --> 00:16:20,538
And of course that's a very suppressive measure, so that sometimes we might wake up feeling better, but it's at the expense of having pushed things down into the psyche, into our psychology.

146
00:16:21,177 --> 00:16:27,212
And that comes out later on as greater feelings of dullness, greater feelings of lethargy.

147
00:16:27,232 --> 00:16:28,937
And so the wheel turns.

148
00:16:29,038 --> 00:16:36,317
And without us knowing, we're just making these little decisions, quite unmindfully, just falling asleep all over the place.

149
00:16:37,511 --> 00:16:48,043
There was once when I was in a monastery and there was a monk there who got himself into this awful state of constantly falling asleep.

150
00:16:49,306 --> 00:17:00,177
And as soon as you sat with him, it was a very strange sort of situation really, but as soon as he came to sit with you, you'd be talking to him and he'd just fall asleep like that.

151
00:17:01,407 --> 00:17:06,733
And he got himself into this dreadful state, and he complained to me that his concentration was very bad.

152
00:17:06,794 --> 00:17:11,460
So I said, well, I said, you've just got to put a bit more energy into life.

153
00:17:12,099 --> 00:17:18,228
And that's one of the pitfalls of the monastic life, because you don't get somebody pushing you.

154
00:17:18,709 --> 00:17:24,194
So eventually, you can fall into this habit of just, as soon as you sit down, you fall asleep.

155
00:17:26,038 --> 00:17:27,819
Now,

156
00:17:27,968 --> 00:17:36,882
It's understanding how we empower these things that begins to make us understand how we can disempower them.

157
00:17:37,232 --> 00:17:48,526
So there's a process, and that's why I chant this dependent origination in the morning, because there the Buddha describes very clearly the process whereby we create this conditioning within ourselves.

158
00:17:49,567 --> 00:18:01,941
So as soon as we have an idea or some feeling, some state enter into our minds, there's a movement towards it.

159
00:18:01,921 --> 00:18:04,025
And that's what he calls this tanha.

160
00:18:04,546 --> 00:18:10,919
Tanha translates as craving, but in a sense that gives us a sort of a wrong impression really.

161
00:18:11,480 --> 00:18:19,255
It's more that there's a desire to indulge it in some way or to resist it in some way.

162
00:18:19,875 --> 00:18:45,411
And it's actually staying with that feeling of resistance, feeling of desire, and not empowering it, not make it do, not doing what it makes you to do, what it wants you to do, that if you stay with that feeling, no matter how strong it is, no matter how uncomfortable it is, stay with it long enough for it to sort of die away, for it to begin to exhaust itself.

163
00:18:45,711 --> 00:18:52,780
And you find that energy, that habitual energy, begins to just fade away.

164
00:18:53,701 --> 00:18:55,364
Because you're not reinforcing it.

165
00:18:55,844 --> 00:19:00,609
It needs, these habits need to be reinforced.

166
00:19:00,670 --> 00:19:02,893
They need new energy to keep going.

167
00:19:04,233 --> 00:19:09,359
I went walking up a hill down in Dingle there with this guy.

168
00:19:09,641 --> 00:19:11,482
And he's a regular mountain climber.

169
00:19:13,083 --> 00:19:15,426
And he climbs two mountains a week.

170
00:19:15,446 --> 00:19:16,048
Can you imagine that?

171
00:19:16,628 --> 00:19:17,470
Two mountains a week.

172
00:19:17,770 --> 00:19:19,153
And in between time he cycles.

173
00:19:20,015 --> 00:19:28,910
And he just says if he stops climbing the mountain, even for a week or so, you know, like there's a loss of stamina.

174
00:19:28,930 --> 00:19:31,934
There's a loss of actual muscle power.

175
00:19:32,438 --> 00:19:43,817
So even at a sort of basic physical level, if you don't keep up that practice, the habit immediately, that habit immediately begins to atrophy, begins to die.

176
00:19:45,141 --> 00:19:50,210
Now, in terms of the parts of ourselves which are negative, that works for us.

177
00:19:50,529 --> 00:19:53,855
All we have to do is not empower an intention.

178
00:19:55,220 --> 00:19:59,169
And in so doing, that habit that we want to get rid of dies away.

179
00:19:59,650 --> 00:20:07,848
And of course, that sounds easy, but anybody who's tried to give up a strong habit knows that it's extraordinarily difficult.

180
00:20:07,990 --> 00:20:13,261
And you've got to keep the effort to just keep letting go, keep letting go.

181
00:20:15,570 --> 00:20:25,640
This phrase that you'll come across, letting go, it's not your letting go of something, it's your allowing something to arise and pass away.

182
00:20:28,281 --> 00:20:41,634
Actually, it's not an active part on our side of letting something go, but more in the sense of being with something and allowing it to arise and allowing it to pass away.

183
00:20:42,193 --> 00:20:44,076
That's what it really means.

184
00:20:46,317 --> 00:21:02,316
So, the final is that we've talked about this identity business and how we have to actually not fall into the mistake of always saying, I am.

185
00:21:04,378 --> 00:21:08,483
In our meditation, we're sort of pulling out of the whole process.

186
00:21:09,105 --> 00:21:10,707
That's what the meditation is about.

187
00:21:10,727 --> 00:21:14,171
It's about showing us a different position that we can take.

188
00:21:14,892 --> 00:21:15,952
So, for instance,

189
00:21:16,539 --> 00:21:44,859
when I've got a pain in the knee from the sitting so I can see immediately that there's a desire to want to move to get rid of the pain but instead of doing that I'm actually being aware of that process of wanting to get rid of the pain of being unable to stay equanimously with pain and then as I watch that I might be surprised to find that that desire disappears

190
00:21:46,003 --> 00:21:55,686
So the consequence of wanting to get away from the pain is something that we've taught ourselves because this doesn't make us happy.

191
00:21:57,210 --> 00:22:02,342
And then when we sit with the pain, when we just sit with it equanimously, we find that there's no suffering.

192
00:22:03,554 --> 00:22:08,603
So we made a distinction between a physical discomfort and a mental state.

193
00:22:09,364 --> 00:22:11,708
And the two become quite separate for us.

194
00:22:12,568 --> 00:22:16,315
And we realize that this suffering is actually a mental position.

195
00:22:16,816 --> 00:22:18,199
It's not a physical position.

196
00:22:18,479 --> 00:22:21,984
The only thing that a physical position can give us is sensation.

197
00:22:22,588 --> 00:22:27,319
Now I'm not suggesting that we get to a point with pain where it's not making us scream.

198
00:22:27,580 --> 00:22:35,157
As soon as we stop learning from pain, there's no point, to my mind anyway, in bearing with it.

199
00:22:35,259 --> 00:22:36,141
We can move, you see.

200
00:22:37,763 --> 00:22:38,645
It's not a macho thing.

201
00:22:38,665 --> 00:22:40,210
You're not trying to defeat pain.

202
00:22:41,522 --> 00:22:43,385
I don't think you'll win, frankly.

203
00:22:43,405 --> 00:22:50,915
So as soon as you recognize this aversion towards pain, then we watch that, you see.

204
00:22:51,276 --> 00:22:54,480
So already I've pulled out of a certain psychology.

205
00:22:55,142 --> 00:22:58,405
Already I've discovered a different position within myself.

206
00:22:58,926 --> 00:23:03,593
Instead of, I don't want, I don't like this pain, I will move away from it.

207
00:23:03,894 --> 00:23:07,578
Suddenly we're saying, there is the desire to move away from pain.

208
00:23:07,659 --> 00:23:09,280
There is dislike.

209
00:23:09,981 --> 00:23:10,061
Huh?

210
00:23:10,648 --> 00:23:15,644
That shift, that shift from I am to there is, is radical.

211
00:23:18,251 --> 00:23:22,042
It's a completely different level of identity.

212
00:23:24,013 --> 00:23:26,798
I'm hoping everybody's shaking.

213
00:23:27,157 --> 00:23:38,973
So when you get an emotional state, you feel depressed or you feel anxious, our normal reactions is to say, I am depressed, I am anxious.

214
00:23:39,335 --> 00:23:42,679
Here you're sitting in your meditation and you feel the depression.

215
00:23:43,079 --> 00:23:46,104
You feel it as a physical state, as a mental state.

216
00:23:46,605 --> 00:23:50,829
You feel your anxiety, you feel your anger, all the usual rubbish.

217
00:23:51,310 --> 00:23:52,873
So as you feel that,

218
00:23:52,853 --> 00:23:57,557
Instead of saying, I am angry, I am, you're saying, there is.

219
00:23:57,757 --> 00:23:59,598
You're pointing to it, saying, there is.

220
00:24:01,240 --> 00:24:03,663
Now that's a radical shift, isn't it, in your position.

221
00:24:03,782 --> 00:24:08,626
Before you were, I am anxious, and now there is anxiety.

222
00:24:09,788 --> 00:24:14,051
That shift in perspective, that shift is a shift of identity.

223
00:24:14,551 --> 00:24:22,219
You're now identifying with that which knows, that which feels, rather than what it feels and what it knows.

224
00:24:23,346 --> 00:24:43,893
Now that little shift of identity, really, when you do that, really investigate it, really be with it, really see what its qualities are, and ask yourself, when my identity is with the knower, with the feeler, with the experiencer, am I actually experiencing suffering?

225
00:24:43,913 --> 00:24:45,034
Is there suffering there?

226
00:24:45,689 --> 00:25:02,601
Even though the situation I'm in may not be particularly good, even though the anxiety creates a mental state, an inner environment, an interior which is not particularly pleasant, am I actually suffering?

227
00:25:03,474 --> 00:25:33,313
so make that very plain to yourself and this constant pulling out from what we're experiencing within ourselves constantly bringing ourselves out into the knower, the feeler, the experiencer is the process whereby we're re-establishing a different identity and so when we do that we can see that all the body is offering us is sensation pain is a mental construct

228
00:25:34,238 --> 00:25:47,621
When you have pain in your knee and you're using a noting word, pain, pain, and you're getting close to it, see if you can bury your attention directly into the sensations that you're calling pain.

229
00:25:48,702 --> 00:25:51,988
When you go deep enough, you'll find that the word pain disappears.

230
00:25:52,269 --> 00:25:55,074
You'll find the word pain disappears and you're using other words.

231
00:25:55,575 --> 00:25:59,300
Perhaps you're using the word pressure or heat.

232
00:25:59,685 --> 00:26:02,450
And at that point, the whole concept of pain disappears.

233
00:26:02,809 --> 00:26:04,393
All you're left with is sensation.

234
00:26:05,314 --> 00:26:09,038
When you pull back a bit, then suddenly the word pain crops up again.

235
00:26:09,820 --> 00:26:19,354
And this is how we begin to realize that pain, suffering, all the stuff that we have, are actually caused by the mind and not by the body.

236
00:26:20,576 --> 00:26:22,638
All the body can offer us is sensation.

237
00:26:24,137 --> 00:26:31,747
Now when it comes to the mind itself, and you've got these painful emotions and stuff, then it's the same process.

238
00:26:31,866 --> 00:26:36,791
As soon as you go into depression, you lose the word depression.

239
00:26:37,192 --> 00:26:37,953
What are you left with?

240
00:26:38,574 --> 00:26:39,915
Heaviness, dullness.

241
00:26:40,696 --> 00:26:47,984
As soon as you stop saying anger and you go into the feel of anger, what words are you using?

242
00:26:48,369 --> 00:26:53,494
fieriness, heat, agitation, but you're not using the word anger.

243
00:26:54,035 --> 00:27:00,441
And as soon as you step back a bit more, as it were, then suddenly the word anger appears in your mind.

244
00:27:01,961 --> 00:27:16,015
And what's happening is that these emotional states, which are actually only feeling states, in the Buddha's vocabulary there's only one word to cover sensation, feelings and emotions as they are experienced in the body.

245
00:27:16,518 --> 00:27:19,721
That's the Vedana that you come across in what we chant.

246
00:27:21,163 --> 00:27:28,432
Then what you realize is that there's a sort of movement of that energy into this higher faculties that we call our imagination and thought.

247
00:27:29,452 --> 00:27:34,699
And it's through the imagination and thought that these emotions are finding expression.

248
00:27:35,200 --> 00:27:38,002
But it's not just expression, they're actually indulging themselves.

249
00:27:38,759 --> 00:27:43,145
So as you know, the more you work on anger, the more angry you get.

250
00:27:44,127 --> 00:27:51,558
The more somebody's upset you and the more you keep bringing it up in your head, then the more angry you get and by the end of the evening you're sort of raging.

251
00:27:52,180 --> 00:27:55,625
You've insulted, you've repeated the insult a hundred thousand times.

252
00:27:55,665 --> 00:28:03,298
They only said it once and you've sort of used it to crank it up so you can go out and have a very good purpose for killing them.

253
00:28:03,970 --> 00:28:08,056
So it's a case of recognizing that it's the mind which is causing the problem.

254
00:28:08,236 --> 00:28:12,722
In the Buddhist understanding, this is proliferation.

255
00:28:13,483 --> 00:28:26,422
So that's why we make this very great effort in meditation, that as soon as the mind wanders and we wake up within it, we note what the attitude is that's propelling the mind into these thought patterns.

256
00:28:27,223 --> 00:28:29,606
We're never concerned with the content.

257
00:28:30,650 --> 00:28:33,093
Now, why is it we're never concerned with the content?

258
00:28:33,413 --> 00:28:37,357
Because it's not the content, it's not the person that's causing the problem.

259
00:28:37,958 --> 00:28:44,766
The problem is deep within ourselves to do with our relationship, our attitude.

260
00:28:45,366 --> 00:28:53,435
So, if somebody shouts at me and says, you stupid, bald-headed monk, you see, that's very painful, isn't it?

261
00:28:53,455 --> 00:28:55,357
I mean, I could get very upset about that.

262
00:28:55,777 --> 00:29:03,601
But actually, it stopped at the ears and it stopped at the heart level where I can perhaps feel their anger towards me.

263
00:29:04,222 --> 00:29:07,392
But that's where, that's all they can do towards me.

264
00:29:08,154 --> 00:29:08,335
Right?

265
00:29:08,617 --> 00:29:21,011
Then, as it were, I take those words inwards, and I chew over them, and I think, who the hell, you know, and then before I know it, I've got myself in a rage over this person who dared to call me that.

266
00:29:21,031 --> 00:29:22,493
And all that's done by me.

267
00:29:22,534 --> 00:29:30,542
If I'd been mindful, I would just have heard these words, stupid, boring, and the feeling of anger, and it could have just stopped there.

268
00:29:32,265 --> 00:29:35,689
And instead, I could have been pouring out my great compassion towards them, you know.

269
00:29:38,707 --> 00:29:45,854
So, what we begin to realize is that nobody actually is causing me suffering.

270
00:29:45,874 --> 00:29:47,276
This is a radical statement.

271
00:29:48,277 --> 00:29:50,558
Nobody can cause us psychological pain.

272
00:29:51,559 --> 00:29:57,807
And once you realize that, then of course, at first, of course, it's a bit disappointing, because it's good to be able to blame somebody.

273
00:29:58,527 --> 00:30:05,734
But in the end, it's actually our liberation, because if I'm causing all this problem, then maybe I can undo it all.

274
00:30:05,755 --> 00:30:07,936
And that's exactly the Buddha's position.

275
00:30:10,211 --> 00:30:29,654
So, our meditation, the actual practice of meditation is this constant effort to come out of what's happening and to observe it, to feel it, to experience what's happening from this vantage point of the knower, the observer, the feeler, the experiencer.

276
00:30:29,634 --> 00:30:45,483
now that's not the end point because there's still a sense of self there I am the knower or I am the one who knows but at least that point is a very objective point and it allows us to see how we're creating the suffering for ourselves

277
00:30:45,463 --> 00:30:51,959
How the world that we are creating is in a constant state of change.

278
00:30:52,278 --> 00:31:02,663
And now every time we fall into an identity with what's happening or a possession of what's happening, some form of unhappiness arises.

279
00:31:03,689 --> 00:31:07,256
Even if it doesn't feel immediate, right?

280
00:31:07,276 --> 00:31:08,920
For instance, when we indulge in something.

281
00:31:09,319 --> 00:31:13,307
So when you're indulging in something, while that's happening, it's pure heaven, see?

282
00:31:13,729 --> 00:31:16,634
It's when it comes to an end that you get the aftermath, okay?

283
00:31:31,397 --> 00:31:43,192
So although you find these loads of books written on Buddhism and heavy philosophy and deep psychology, actually speaking it's extraordinarily simple.

284
00:31:44,294 --> 00:32:00,492
All you have to do is just find this position in yourself, make sure that you know it quite clearly as to this observation post, that's a happy phrase by one writer, an observation post within ourselves, and you just watch.

285
00:32:01,080 --> 00:32:05,484
You just feel what's arising, just experience what's arising.

286
00:32:06,726 --> 00:32:13,291
This intelligence which is liberating itself from the delusion, where does this delusion lie?

287
00:32:14,073 --> 00:32:15,074
It lies in the looking.

288
00:32:15,875 --> 00:32:17,796
It doesn't lie in the body.

289
00:32:17,836 --> 00:32:19,958
The body isn't deluded, the body is just the body.

290
00:32:20,959 --> 00:32:22,721
Emotions don't know themselves, do they?

291
00:32:23,421 --> 00:32:25,242
Emotions can't reflect upon themselves.

292
00:32:25,784 --> 00:32:30,548
There's some intelligence within us which is not looking correctly

293
00:32:30,950 --> 00:32:40,241
one good example of that is, you know, these stigmatisms in people's lenses, in their eyes.

294
00:32:41,603 --> 00:32:43,365
I mean, I'm supposed to have one, you see.

295
00:32:44,145 --> 00:32:52,916
And it's like, you know, in the old glass where you've got that wavy because, you know, they hadn't perfected the way of making glass and you've got that wave.

296
00:32:53,919 --> 00:32:55,361
It's a distortion, you see.

297
00:32:55,820 --> 00:32:58,964
But actually, if you've got one in your eye,

298
00:32:59,738 --> 00:33:01,580
you can't really tell it's there.

299
00:33:02,319 --> 00:33:04,563
It's really a very strange thing, but it's there.

300
00:33:04,623 --> 00:33:06,565
It's somehow distorting your sight.

301
00:33:07,286 --> 00:33:11,851
It's like a person who's colorblind, who's never been told they're colorblind.

302
00:33:12,551 --> 00:33:14,714
And they see the colors what they see.

303
00:33:14,734 --> 00:33:17,097
It's just that not everybody else is looking.

304
00:33:17,478 --> 00:33:19,000
Nobody else sees that.

305
00:33:19,019 --> 00:33:21,162
They're completely happy in the world that they've created.

306
00:33:21,201 --> 00:33:23,325
So it's the same with us.

307
00:33:23,905 --> 00:33:30,993
We've created this world for ourselves coming from a distortion which we're not fully aware of.

308
00:33:31,565 --> 00:33:36,003
And we keep blaming the world, we keep blaming others, we keep blaming ourselves.

309
00:33:36,444 --> 00:33:41,827
But actually the fundamental problem lies in the way that we're looking, the way we're relating.

310
00:33:44,051 --> 00:34:09,199
So, as we pull out from the body with its sensations, pleasant or unpleasant, you pull out from the heart with its emotional states, pleasant or unpleasant, as you begin to observe these thoughts that are coming through and not getting caught up in them, we're constantly correcting this stigmatism that's in the way we're looking.

311
00:34:09,179 --> 00:34:17,047
And the Buddha is very clear about how that stigmatism is destroyed, completely taken out of the equation.

312
00:34:17,806 --> 00:34:21,311
And he says, just observe that things are rising and passing away.

313
00:34:22,072 --> 00:34:29,438
So when you do that, when you realize that everything is rising and passing away, never repeats itself, then you immediately start letting go.

314
00:34:29,478 --> 00:34:32,661
What's the point of holding on to something which is going to disappear?

315
00:34:34,804 --> 00:34:38,847
And the radical position is that there is nothing in the world worth holding on to.

316
00:34:39,942 --> 00:34:49,231
And then when you realize that this relationship we have of always seeking happiness in the world, can we be in the world in a different way?

317
00:34:49,632 --> 00:34:59,702
Can we just appreciate it, enjoy it, without holding on to it, without defining our happiness by what we experience, by what we have, by our mental state?

318
00:35:01,242 --> 00:35:04,887
And then finally there's this business of identity, right?

319
00:35:07,516 --> 00:35:08,980
And we do that through meditation.

320
00:35:09,041 --> 00:35:10,704
We do that through pointing at something.

321
00:35:10,746 --> 00:35:21,036
That's the noting techniques, extremely good at sort of making us be very clear that what I'm experiencing is not me, not mine, because I'm actually pointing to it.

322
00:35:41,248 --> 00:35:44,014
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

323
00:35:44,817 --> 00:35:53,114
May you continue to put great effort in your meditation and be liberated from suffering sooner rather than later.

